ğŸ“Œ Recursive functions C programming mein functions hai jo apne aap ko repeatedly call karte hai. Isse aapko ek problem ko solve karne mein help mil sakta hai jo recursive nature ke hisab se solve kiya jata hai.

ğŸ“Œ Recursive function ke 2 main parts hai:

ğŸ“ 1: Base Case: Base case ek condition hota hai jisme function ko apne aap ko stop karne ke liye kaam karna hoga.

ğŸ“ 2: Recursive Case: Recursive case ek condition hota hai jisme function apne aap ko call karte hai.

Example:

#include <stdio.h>

int factorial(int n) {
    if (n == 0) {
        return 1;
    } else {
        return n * factorial(n - 1);
    }
}

int main() {
    int num = 5;
    int result = factorial(num);
    printf("The factorial of %d is %d\n", num, result);
    return 0;
}

ğŸ“Œ Is example mein, 'factorial' function recursive function hai jo n ka factorial calculate karta hai. 'factorial' function ke 1 base case hai jisme n == 0 hai aur iska return 1 hota hai. Agar n != 0 hai to function apne aap ko n * factorial(n - 1) se call karta hai.

ğŸ“Œ Recursive functions ke use se aapko code ko modular aur organized banane mein help karta hai aur code ka reuse bhi ho jata hai. Agar aap ek function ka use repeat karne ki jarurat hai, to aap usko ek baar define karke, repeatedly use kar sakte hai.

